\begin{document}
% Title Page Information
\title{Strain-Induced Flat Bands and Lateral Heterostructures: \ Hole Localization in Rippled TMDs Monolayers}
\author{Meshal Alawein}
\degreesemester{Spring}
\degreeyear{2025}
\degree{Doctor of Philosophy}
\chair{Professor Ali Javey}
\othermembers{Professor Daryl Chrzan \\
Professor Boubacar Kant\'e}
\numberofmembers{3}
\field{Electrical Engineering and Computer Sciences}
% Front Matter
\maketitle
\approvalpage
\copyrightpage
\chapter*{Abstract}
This thesis investigates how periodic rippling in two-dimensional (2D) group-VI transition metal dichalcogenide (TMD) monolayers---such as MoS\textsubscript{2}, WS\textsubscript{2}, MoSe\textsubscript{2}, and WSe\textsubscript{2}---can induce flat electronic bands under uniaxial compression. Through first-principles simulations, we trace the formation of periodic ripples and show that, beyond a certain compression, flat valence bands emerge in these otherwise semiconducting TMDs.\ In particular, a mechanical-electronic transition unfolds:\ initial deformation leads to buckling, which triggers the formation of ripples---much like a thin sheet forced to bend under pressure.\ This symmetry breaking reshapes the electronic structure: as compression increases, the $\Gamma$-point (hosting a nearly flat segment along the $\overline{\Gamma X}$ direction) rises in energy, while the K-point (initially the valence band maximum) drops. At a critical compression, these levels cross---ushering the birth of a flat valence band and a fundamental shift in the material’s properties.\ The resulting system forms a built-in lateral heterostructure---entirely within a chemically uniform monolayer---achieved without stacking, twisting, or chemical doping.\ Curvature acts as the driving parameter, and the outcome is striking:\ heavy-hole states are pinned in high-curvature regions, while electrons remain free to move.\ This electronic asymmetry opens pathways for exciton trapping, anisotropic hole transport, and exploration of correlated electronic phases in 2D systems. 

