\section{Localization of Hole States}

To probe carrier localization under compression, Figures~\ref{fig:S9}--\ref{fig:S11} plot the probability densities for conduction band minimum (CBM) and valence band maximum (VBM) states for each material across selected compression levels.

Key findings:

\begin{itemize}
    \item For all TMDs, conduction electrons remain broadly delocalized, even after substantial buckling.
    \item Hole states progressively localize at ripple peaks and valleys after the direct-to-indirect transition.
    \item Sulfur-containing compounds (MoS\textsubscript{2}, WS\textsubscript{2}) display slightly sharper hole localization at lower compressions than selenium compounds (MoSe\textsubscript{2}, WSe\textsubscript{2}), consistent with their stronger orbital hybridization under strain.
\end{itemize}

Thus, the formation of curvature-defined lateral heterostructures by mechanical compression appears to be a **generalizable design rule** for 2D TMD monolayers.

