\section{Summary}

The behavior observed in MoS\textsubscript{2}---band flattening, direct-to-indirect transitions, and curvature-induced hole localization---extends robustly across multiple group-VI TMD monolayers.

Although critical compression thresholds vary slightly depending on chalcogen species, the underlying physics appears universal:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Mechanical buckling} reorganizes the band structure in all materials studied.
    \item \textbf{Curvature-driven flat bands} emerge at the valence band edge after sufficient compression.
    \item \textbf{Hole states localize} at ripple-induced potential wells, while electron states remain delocalized.
\end{itemize}

Thus, mechanical curvature emerges as a general strategy for engineering quantum states in flexible, atomically thin materials.

\chapter{Primer on Band Theory, DFT, and Rippling Physics}
\label{app:AppendixC}

\section{Electronic Band Theory Basics}

In crystalline solids, the periodic arrangement of atoms gives rise to energy bands---allowed ranges of electron energies---separated by forbidden gaps.

Key concepts:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Bloch's Theorem}: Electronic wavefunctions in a periodic potential take the form $\psi_{\mathbf{k}}(\mathbf{r}) = e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}} u_{\mathbf{k}}(\mathbf{r})$, where $u_{\mathbf{k}}(\mathbf{r})$ has the periodicity of the lattice.
    \item \textbf{Band Structure}: Solving the Schrödinger equation with a periodic potential yields a dispersion relation $E(\mathbf{k})$ between energy and crystal momentum.
    \item \textbf{Effective Mass}: Near band extrema (e.g., conduction minima, valence maxima), carriers behave like free particles but with modified inertia determined by band curvature.
    \item \textbf{Flat Bands}: Bands with very low dispersion ($\partial^2 E/\partial k^2 \approx 0$) correspond to localized electronic states and high density of states---fertile ground for correlation-driven phenomena.
\end{itemize}

\section{Density Functional Theory (DFT) Overview}

Density functional theory (DFT) provides a practical framework for calculating electronic structures of many-body systems based on the electron density $\rho(\mathbf{r})$ rather than the full many-electron wavefunction.

Key principles:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Hohenberg-Kohn Theorems}: The ground-state properties of an interacting electron system are uniquely determined by its ground-state density.
    \item \textbf{Kohn-Sham Equations}: A fictitious system of non-interacting electrons is introduced, whose density matches that of the real system, greatly simplifying calculations.
    \item \textbf{Exchange-Correlation Functional}: The many-body effects are encapsulated in an approximate exchange-correlation energy functional. Common approximations include LDA, GGA (e.g., PBE used here).
    \item \textbf{Band Gap Underestimation}: Standard DFT functionals typically underestimate semiconductor band gaps, though trends in band structure evolution (e.g., under strain) are often reliable.
\end{itemize}

In this work, DFT calculations were performed using the generalized gradient approximation (GGA) and norm-conserving pseudopotentials.

\section{Physics of Rippling and Buckling in 2D Materials}

Unlike bulk crystals, two-dimensional materials like MoS\textsubscript{2} have extraordinary flexibility in-plane but are easily perturbed out-of-plane.

Key mechanical behaviors:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Buckling Instability}: When compressive strain exceeds a critical value, a flat sheet minimizes its elastic energy by forming periodic out-of-plane ripples.
    \item \textbf{Sinusoidal Rippling}: At moderate strains, the ripples tend to assume sinusoidal profiles, characterized by a wavelength $\lambda$ and amplitude $A$.
    \item \textbf{Strain-Defined Potentials}: In strained 2D materials, local variations in curvature and strain can modulate electronic band edges, effectively creating built-in potential landscapes without chemical heterogeneity.
    \item \textbf{Curvature-Induced Band Modulation}: Bond angles and orbital overlaps are highly sensitive to curvature, leading to shifts in conduction and valence band energies at the atomic scale.
\end{itemize}

In the systems studied here, rippling induced by uniaxial compression along the armchair direction leads to a periodic modulation of the valence band, promoting flat band formation and hole localization.

\section{Summary}

This primer provides essential background for understanding the key physical mechanisms underlying the results presented in the main thesis:

- How periodic potentials sculpt electronic bands.
- How DFT enables their computation.
- How mechanical deformation---particularly rippling---can act as an emergent tool for band engineering in two-dimensional materials.

The interplay between crystal symmetry, electronic structure, and mechanical geometry stands at the heart of the phenomena investigated in this work.



